==Old English==

===Etymology===
Germanic ''frîþ-'', from Indo-European ''*prāy-, *prēy-'' ‘like, love’.
There are cognates in Old Frisian [[fretho]], Old Saxon [[frithu]] (Dutch [[vrede]]), Old High German [[fridu]] (German [[Friede]]), Old Norse [[friðr]] (Swedish and Danish [[fred]]).  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[πραυς]], Slavonic ''*prьjatī'' (Old Church Slavonic [[прити]], Russian [[приять]] ‘friend’), Old Irish [[ríar]] (Welsh [[rhydd]] ‘free’).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /frɪθ/

